<p><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size=-1><b>Midwest Book Review: </b>"an
exultant relationship drama that fans of contemporary tales will enjoy."</font></font>
<p><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size=-1><b>The Danforth Review:
</b>"deeply
heartfelt... the ending of this book was like a large blast of fireworks."</font></font>
<p><b><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size=-1>Bruce Gillespie <i>(editor,
SF Commentary, in *</i>brg*<i>)</i>: </font></font></b><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size=-1>"<i>St
Patrick's Bed</i>...&nbsp; has a natty ghost story hidden in it, but at
heart it's an ambitious book about the most interesting subject of all:
how best can we live, given the limited choices offered to most of us?...
The temptation is to read this as a simple book, but its multiple echoes
and possibilities give it an epic scope. At 220 pages, <i>St. Patrick's
Bed </i>is one of few recent novels that has the right length."</font></font>
<p><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font size=-1><b>Dayton Daily News: </b>"the
book is genuine"</font></font>
